what are the state managements

1. Component State (Local State)

What it is:

State stored inside a component.

count = 0;

increment() {
  this.count++;
}


2. Service-based State (Singleton Services)

What it is:

Using Angular services to share state.

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CounterService {
  count = 0;
}
Use when:
Small apps
Shared state across components
Pros:
Easy to implement
Built-in DI system
Cons:
No structure for large apps
Hard to debug as app grows

🔹 3. RxJS-based State (BehaviorSubject)
What it is:

Reactive state using RxJS.
private count$ = new BehaviorSubject<number>(0);

increment() {
  this.count$.next(this.count$.value + 1);
}

Use when:
Need reactive updates
Medium complexity apps
Pros:
Reactive
Works well with Angular
Cons:
Boilerplate
Harder to manage at scale

🔹 4. Signals (Modern Angular - recommended)

Introduced in Angular 16+

What it is:

Reactive primitives built into Angular.
import { signal } from '@angular/core';

count = signal(0);

increment() {
  this.count.update(c => c + 1);
}
Use when:
Modern Angular apps
Simpler reactive state without RxJS
Pros:
Simple
High performance
Fine-grained reactivity
Cons:
Still evolving ecosystem


Angular optimization case study :


🧩 Scenario: Enterprise Analytics Dashboard

🚨 Initial Problems
❌ Symptoms
UI lag (~2–4 seconds delay)
CPU spikes in browser
Frequent re-renders
Memory leaks over time
🔍 Root Causes
1. Global state updates triggering full re-render
this.dashboardData$.next(newData);

👉 Every widget re-rendered on any change

2. Default Change Detection everywhere
changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default

👉 Entire component tree checked repeatedly

3. Large lists without trackBy
<div *ngFor="let row of data">

👉 DOM recreated unnecessarily

4. Over-fetching data
this.http.get('/dashboard-data') // huge payload

👉 Sending entire dataset even if only 1 widget needed up

date

5. Too many RxJS emissions
Polling + multiple .next() calls
No throttling or deduplication
6. Manual subscriptions everywhere
this.service.data$.subscribe(...)

👉 Memory leaks + redundant updates

🔧 Optimization Strategy
✅ 1. Switch to OnPush Change Detection
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
Impact:
Components update only when inputs change
Reduced change detection cycles by ~70%
✅ 2. Split Global State into Feature State
❌ Before
dashboardState = {
  users,
  revenue,
  orders,
  alerts
}
✅ After
users$ = this.store.select(selectUsers);
revenue$ = this.store.select(selectRevenue);
Impact:
Only affected widgets re-render
Eliminated unnecessary UI updates
✅ 3. Introduce Signals (Hybrid Migration)
users = signal<User[]>([]);

updateUsers(data: User[]) {
  this.users.set(data);
}
Impact:
Fine-grained updates
Only dependent UI parts refresh

✅ 4. Optimize Lists with trackBy
<tr *ngFor="let row of data; trackBy: trackById">
trackById(index: number, item: any) {
  return item.id;
}
Impact:
DOM reuse
Huge performance boost for large tables

✅ 5. Reduce API Payload (Backend + Frontend)
❌ Before
GET /dashboard-data
✅ After
GET /dashboard/users
GET /dashboard/revenue
Impact:
Smaller payloads
Faster network + parsing
✅ 6. Control RxJS Emissions
this.data$
  .pipe(
    debounceTime(500),
    distinctUntilChanged()
  )
Impact:
Reduced UI updates
Prevented rapid re-renders
✅ 7. Replace Manual Subscriptions with Async Pipe
<div *ngFor="let user of users$ | async"></div>
Impact:
Auto unsubscribe
Cleaner code
Better performance
✅ 8. Virtual Scrolling (Huge Win)

Using Angular CDK:

<cdk-virtual-scroll-viewport itemSize="50">
  <div *cdkVirtualFor="let item of data">
    {{ item.name }}
  </div>
</cdk-virtual-scroll-viewport>
Impact:
Render only visible items (~20 instead of 10,000)
Massive DOM reduction
✅ 9. Memoized Selectors (NgRx)
export const selectUsers = createSelector(
  selectDashboard,
  state => state.users
);
Impact:
Prevents unnecessary recomputation
Faster UI updates
✅ 10. Lazy Load Heavy Widgets
loadComponent(() => import('./heavy-chart.component'))
Impact:
Faster initial load
Reduced bundle size
📊 Final Results (Measured)
Metric	Before	After
Initial Load Time	6.5 sec	2.1 sec
UI Response Time	2–4 sec lag	<500 ms
Change Detection Runs	~1000+	~200


Memory Usage	High/leaking	Stable
DOM Nodes	~15,000	~2,000
🧠 Key Learnings
🔥 Biggest wins came from:
OnPush change detection
State slicing (not global updates)
Virtual scrolling
Signals for fine-grained updates
⚠️ What didn’t help much
Micro-optimizing small functions
Premature caching
Overusing RxJS operators unnecessarily
🧠 Interview-ready answer

“In a large Angular dashboard, we improved performance by switching to OnPush change detection, splitting global state into feature-level observables, introducing Signals for fine-grained updates, and using virtual scrolling for large datasets. These changes reduced re-renders significantly and improved UI responsiveness from seconds to sub-500ms.


WHAT IS @output

@output is a decorator that creates a custome event in a child component.
The parent component can listen to this event and react when it happens

use @output when
1. a button is clicked in a child component
2. a form is sumbmitted in a child component
3. data changes in a child and the parent must know

Child Component  ---- emits event ---->  Parent Component

child component:
import { Component, Output, EventEmitter } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: `
    <button (click)="sendMessage()">Send to Parent</button>
  `
})
export class ChildComponent {

  @Output() messageEvent = new EventEmitter<string>();

  sendMessage() {
    this.messageEvent.emit('Hello from Child!');
  }
}

🔹 @Output() marks an event
🔹 EventEmitter sends the data
🔹 .emit() triggers the event


parent component :
<app-child (messageEvent)="receiveMessage($event)"></app-child>

<p>{{ message }}</p>

✅ $event contains the data sent from the child.

---------------------------------------
✅ Output with Form Example
@output() submitForm = new EventEmitter<any>();
this.submitForm.emit(this.form.value);

parent :
<app-child (submitForm)="onFormSubmit($event)"></app-child>

✅ Difference Between @Input and @Output

 
DecoratorDirection@Input()Parent → Child@Output()Child → Parent

why do you use observable in aNGULAR?
Angular applications deals hevily with asynchronouse data and observables provide a powerful
consitent and scalable way to handle it
an observable is a stream of data that
1. it can emit multiple values over time
2. it can subscribed and can be cancelled
3. can be transformed using operators
4. is lazy (executes only when subscribed)

Angular apps constantly work with async data such as:
1. http api calls
2. user input events
3 route changes

2️⃣ Supports Multiple Values Over Time
Unlike Promises (which return one value only), Observables can return many values.
✅ Perfect for:

Live data
Real-time updates
Form value changes
4. webscoket data
5. timers


3️⃣ Cancel or Unsubscribe (Memory Safety)
Observables can be unsubscribed, preventing memory leaks.
subscription.unsubscribe();

✅ Promises cannot be cancelled
✅ Observables can be stopped anytime
This is why Angular uses Observables in:

HTTP requests
Router events
Components lifecycle

4️⃣ Powerful Data Transformation (RxJS Operators)
Observables can be transformed easily using operators like:

map
filter
switchMap
debounceTime
mergeMap


5️⃣ Lazy Execution (Better Performance)
const obs$ = this.http.get('/api/data'); // not executed yet

obs$.subscribe(); // executed now

Angular provides async pipe to auto‑subscribe and auto‑unsubscribe.
7️⃣ Works Perfectly With Async Pipe
<div *ngIf="users$ | async as users">
  {{ users.length }}
</div>
✅ No manual unsubscribe
✅ Cleaner templates
✅ Prevents memory leaks

1️⃣ To Handle Asynchronous Operations
2️⃣ Supports Multiple Values Over Time
3️⃣ Cancel or Unsubscribe (Memory Safety)
4️⃣ Powerful Data Transformation (RxJS Operators)
5️⃣ Lazy Execution (Better Performance)
6️⃣ Consistency Across Angular Framework
7️⃣ Works Perfectly With Async Pipe

Angular uses Observables because they efficiently
handle asynchronous data streams, support multiple values, can be cancelled,
and integrate seamlessly with RxJS and Angular features.

Guards decide whether navigation is allowed, while Interceptors handle API‑level authentication like attaching JWT tokens
and handling HTTP errors.\
They solve different problems and are used together.

JWT is stateless authentication
Token expiration improves security
Refresh token avoids forced logout
Guards protect routes
Interceptors protect API calls
